<tt>Wed May 14 22:30:13 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Spatz,<br><br>
Thanks for the story.<br><br>
In it I saw alot of me - the drugs and the rebellion. Only my radicalism came AFTER Vietnam. Some learn the hard way.<br><br>
For whatever reasons, some of us have to learn in a different way. For all the conflict, then and now, I feel that we are standing on the same common ground. <br><br>
What Doc Del calls &quot;inconsistencies&quot;, I would much rather call change or growth. I know. Much of what I once denounced I have grown to comprehend. It is much like when I looked into the mirror one day and saw my father staring back at me. Much of what he said fell on deaf ears. I understand what he meant now. <br><br>
We put our trust in our leaders when wars come about. Some questioned the leadership during those days of our youth. <br>
We all have come to find out just how wrong our leaders were.<br><br>
During the Gulf War, our casualties - when compared with Iraqs - were unbelievably disproportianate.<br><br>
You mentioned how there was not a memorial for those who protested back in the 1960's. I beg to differ. There were no Hamburger Hill's or Khe Sanh's or hopeless frontal assaults in the Gulf. True, topography and other factors must be considered as contributing to the success of the US and its allies. But, the underlying factor - which was everpresent whenever military policy or tactics were being formulated - was &quot;what will the people say if we screw up?&quot; This is a direct result of the Vietnam years - when people dared to speak out in order to be heard. There is your memorial, and it is alive and well today. Free speech.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


